{
  "text": "the apical microleakage of roots filled with the system B, lateral compaction, vertical compaction and Thermafil using a fluid filtration system. This study indicated that Thermafil is as effective at sealing the apex as lateral compaction, vertical compaction, and system B when tested immediately. However, after 1 month, lateral compaction presents higher leakage. [CITATION_1] The authors explained this to be due to the larger amount of sealer in the apical 1 mm when compared with Thermafil. In another study, there was no significant difference in the sealing ability of Thermafil obturators when compared with cold lateral compaction of gutta-percha as long as a sealer was used. Thermafil obturators without a sealer resulted in significantly greater dye penetration when compared with Thermafil with sealer. [CITATION_2] This observation agrees with a previous dye leakage study. [CITATION_3] These results indicated that a root-canal sealer is essential although the alpha-phase transformation to beta-phase in Thermafil is associated with shrinkage of thermoplasticized gutta-percha, the presence of sealer can obviously help offset any contraction of the Thermafil gutta-percha mass.",
  "correct_citation": {
